$n$\backslash$nP$\backslash$nor Q$\backslash$n$\backslash$nS$\backslash$nzones, which is consistent with reported crustal reflectivity. In general, for the southern California crust, Q$\backslash$n$\backslash$nS$\backslash$n/Q$\backslash$n$\backslash$nP$\backslash$nis greater than 1.0, suggesting partially fluid-saturated crust. A few limited regions of Q$\backslash$n$\backslash$nS$\backslash$n/Q$\backslash$n$\backslash$nP$\backslash$nless than 1.0 correspond to areas mostly outside the major sedimentary basins, including areas around the San Jacinto fault, suggesting a larger reduction in the shear modulus compared to the bulk modulus or almost complete fluid saturation.},
